\begin_layout Subsection
Instability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2D1V simulations are run by restarting from the converged,
 steady-state 1D1V profiles and adding some random noise with relative amplitude 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-9}$
\end_inset

 to the density - i.e.
 density is multiplied by a factor 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+10^{-9}\mathtt{rand()})$
\end_inset

 at each point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a simple measure of the mode amplitude at a given time,
 we look at the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 profiles,
 remove the background by taking the root-mean-square over the 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

-dimension,
 then take the maximum over 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\max_{z}\left(\sqrt{\frac{\sum_{r}\left(\phi-\left\langle \phi\right\rangle _{r}\right)^{2}}{n_{r}}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \phi\right\rangle _{r}=\frac{\sum_{r}\phi}{n_{r}}$
\end_inset

 is the mean over 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 This measure is a bit crude - it just averages the grid point values,
 ignoring the finite-element nature of the grid,
 but should be good enough because the simulations show a long period of linear growth with a more or less unchanging eigenvector.
\end_layout

